<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Environmental Audit Committee Inquiry into the Code for Sustainable Homes and the Housing Standards Review</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence submitted by Richard </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Hodkinson</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Consultancy</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Executive Summary</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Richard Hodkinson Consultancy is an award winning environmental and energy consultancy with a focus on th</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e housing sector. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We agree with the strategic aim of the Housing Standards Review consultation that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ousing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tandards should be properly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> consolidated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">into Building Regulations. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Nationally Described Standards as proposed in the Housing Standard Review consultation are technically incomplete. It is concerning that a proper set of Nationally Described Standards </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was not produced.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are concerned that robust compliance methods have not been set out for the Nationally Described Standards. Without effective compliance, a Housing Standards vacuum would be created which will result in a reduction of quality of new housing. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To address the weaknesses of the government’s proposed approach, our proposals are two-fold:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A properly funded National Centre of Excellence for Housing Standards be established to ensure, independently, that Housing Standards are appropriate and viable;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 68.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">That the Code for Sustainable Homes is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">fully revised for the Nationally Described Standards to provide a robust compliance methodology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transitional arrangement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> until the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uilding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">egulation route is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">established</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">About Richard </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Hodkinson</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> Consultancy</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Richard Hodkinson Consultancy is an award winning consultancy specialising in energy and environmental advice with a focus </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> residential development. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The company employs an integrated professional team of chartered surveyors, chartered engineers, chartered builders and chartered town planners and is actively working on over 200 housing projects. Within the team there are a number of Code for Sustainable Homes, energy and BREEAM accredited assessors.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For the last 15 years t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he company has played a pivotal role in raising the environmental performance of UK housing. The practice is retained on four of the largest housing projects in the UK and last year we undertook more Code for Sustainable Homes assessments than any other organisation. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The scope of our work ranges from concept design, planning consent, detailed design through to post-construction environmental assessment. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Integration of Housing Standards into Building Regulations</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is clear that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ousing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tandards, where they are deemed important enough, should be incorporated into Building Regulations. This is the ultimate goal of the government as expressed in the consultation document and we support this approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We understand that good, sustainable design should be the bedrock of Building Regulations and that the clarity and consistency </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of this approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is good for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">home buyers, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">house-builders as well as the supply chain.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s noted in the consultation document, there are a number of disadvantages to this approach, as well as difficulties in the implementation. One of the main constraints on this approach is the requirement for one single and integrated set of Building Regulations to be applied nationwide and be fully supported by a strong evidence base.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It remains to be seen how complex such Building Regulations would be. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The Scope of the Nationally Described Standards </span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">efore the route to adopting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ousing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tandards in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uilding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">egulations has been agreed, the government is proposing a set of ‘Nationally Described Standards’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which may be adopted by local authorities.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is self-evident from the Housing Standards Review consultation document that a proper set of technically well considered standards was not generated by the Housing Standards Working Groups. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proposed Nationally Described Standards scope is technically incomplete and inadequate. As identified by the Challenge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Panel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Review report, not all technical issues have been adequately covered by the review. This will not meet the government’s intention of effectively delivering high quality sustainable housing.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are also concerned that serious technical issues are trivialised by the consultation document. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Topics which are central to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Housing Standards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, such as materials, NOx pollution, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">internal drying of clothes, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ecology as well as daylighting are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> essentially</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> proposed to be removed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ousing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tandards and left to the market. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The close interaction of daylighting, solar gain and over-heating issues in response to glazing specification and masterplanning is omitted.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Housing Standards Review has focused on issues relating to the technical performance of dwellings. This approach does not consider the array of issues that affect both the technical performance and local environmental</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The Code</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for Sustainable Homes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has provided a useful method for assessing sustainability issues that sit on the boundary of technical and environmental issues.  This view is also echoed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Challenge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Panel Review</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, which considers the Code</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for Sustainable Homes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has not been ‘properly deconstructed’. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In order to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ousing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tandards going forwa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rd are technically appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and address local nee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d where appropriate, we propose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that a National Centre of Excellence is established</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for Housing Standards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">entre would be responsible for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">benchmarking international practice, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">coordinating</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> research and innovation and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disseminating </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">best practice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Central to this role would be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cost-benefit analysis and viability testing of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ousing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tandards. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Historically this role would have been undertaken by BRE (formerly the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overnment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Building Research Establishment)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. It is acknowledged that a wider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">range of stakeholders need to be properly involved in this process. Housing S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tandards </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to be founded on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">scientifically </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and practically </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">focused research.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The consultation is proposing that voluntary standards may be applied to fill gaps in the National</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ly Described</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Standards. However, in a market where housing supply is historically not able to meet demand, we are concerned that without suitable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">compliance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mechanisms in place, voluntary standards will not adequately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">deliver</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> high-quality </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sustainable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">housing. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Compliance Mechanisms for the Nationally Described Standards</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In addition to our concerns relating to the scope of the Nationally Described Standards, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we do not consider that robust compliance procedures have been set out in the consultation document. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although compliance mechanisms for standards within the Building Regulations have been set out there is no such clarity with regard to the Nationally Described Standards. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ur primary concern is that until </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ousing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tandards can be appropriately set within Building Regulations, appropriate transitional arrangements need to be in place to ensure that high quality homes continue to be delivered. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The premature withdrawal of the Code for Sustainable Homes before a suitable compliance mechanism is in place will create a Housing Standards vacuum which will drive down standards. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We therefore consider that the Nationally Described Standards should be strengthened into </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a fully revised </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Code for Sustainable Homes as part of the transitional arrangements to the Building Regulations approach.  The Code for Sustainable Homes has a well-defined compliance methodology in place</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which could reflect the single suite of Nationally Described Standards.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Code for Sustainable Homes has positively driven forward standards across the market, acting as a pathfinder for some issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and covering many other issues that fall between planning and regulation (such as NOx emissions described earlier). An</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">updated Code for Sustainable Homes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">could be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">central to the proposed Nationally Described Standards, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">would then act as a pathfinder for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proposed changes to the Building Regulations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">An updated Code for Sustainable Homes could also include ‘top-up’ standards which may never be integrated into regulation (such as higher accessibility standards).</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A ratings system could be maintained to address the disparities nationwide in terms of viability, but mandatory requirements (that are considered of local importance) could be cherry picked by local authorities where required. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Crucially, all of the Nationally Described Standards would be reflected in this single Code for Sustainable Homes, with no reference to third party standards or room for proliferation. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We accept that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the current Code for Sustainable Homes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has a number of limitations: some contradiction with other standards, a perception of being obsolete, and higher levels which are widely considered to be unviable for volume house-builders to achieve. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Code for Sustainable Homes is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">long </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overdue an update. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Code for Sustainable Homes Advisory Group has not met since March 2010 which has resulted in some frustration. The last revision to the Code for Sustainable Homes was in November 2010. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We feel that if the Code for Sustainable Homes had been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">better</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">managed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">then it would have retained its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">relevance and would</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> still</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be perceived as a driver for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">better Housing Standards that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be properly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">house-builders,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">home buyers, the supply chain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and local authorities alike. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proposed National Centre of Excellence would set the content of the revised Code for Sustainable Homes and ensure that it was properly maintained.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This approach also ensures that high quality</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Housing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tandards continue to be delivered</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> while providing some continuity and stability to the market. We consider it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vital to make use of existing resources and processes during the transitional arrangements in the move to Building Regulations. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> Summary</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We support the strategic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">view that H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ousing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tandards should be properly incorporated into the Building Regulations. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As identified in the consultation, there is uncertainty </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on the part of CLG and the Challenge Panel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as to how best this may be achieved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">obust </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transitional arrangements </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are required to address sustainability and quality issues in the meantime.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he government is proposing a set of ‘Nationally Described Standards’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which may be adopted by local authorities, until the Building Regulation route is defined</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We have two key concerns with the Nationally Described Standards: that the scope of the proposed Housing Standards is incomplete, and that it fails to clearly set out an appropriate methodology to demonstrate compliance.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are therefore concerned that the quality of housing delivered to the market would be reduced, and that housing research and innovation would be dis-incentivised. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our proposals are therefore twofold:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A properly funded National Centre of Excellence for Housing Standards be established to ensure, independently, that Housing Standards are appropriate and viable;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 68.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">That the Code for Sustainable Homes is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">fully reviewed for the Nationally Described Standards to provide a robust compliance methodology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transitional arrangement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> until the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uilding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">egulation route is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">established</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">2 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>